long_desc.thetext:
I just checked how that would be posible to write a cell renderer and it should be pretty easy for the select box case. Just extend the Replace cell renderer and override _getContentHtml method. In that, you can call the base method and then add your own stuff around the HTML. Just take a look at the prototype I wrote to test the whole stuff:


qx.Class.define("qx.ui.table.cellrenderer.ReplaceSelectBox",
{
  extend : qx.ui.table.cellrenderer.Replace,

  members :
  {
    // overridden
    _getContentHtml : function(cellInfo) {
      var decorator = qx.theme.manager.Decoration.getInstance().resolve("button-css");
      var styles = decorator._getStyles();
      styles["width"] = (cellInfo.styleWidth - 7) + "px";
      styles["height"] = (cellInfo.styleHeight - 7) + "px";
      styles["padding"] = "2px";
      styles["color"] = qx.theme.manager.Color.getInstance().resolve("table-row");
      styles = qx.bom.element.Style.compile(styles);
      console.log(cellInfo.row, cellInfo);
      return "<div style='" + styles + "'>" + this.base(arguments, cellInfo) + "</div>";
    }
  }
});


As I don't exactly know how you think the UI should look I would ask you for either more input or just implement the look as you would like it in a custom renderer.

